ations', Academy of Management Journal, 38 (1), February, 24-59 -- Walter W. Powell (1996), 'Trust-Based Forms of Governance', in Roderick M. Kramer (ed) and Tom R. Tyler (ed) (eds), Trust in Organizations: Frontiers of Theory and Research, Chapter 4, Thousand Oaks, CA: Sage Publications, Inc., 51-67 -- Patrick A. Saparito, Chao C. Chen and Harry J. Sapienza (2004), 'The Role of Relational Trust in Bank-Small Firm Relationships', Academy of Management Journal, 47 (3), June, 400-10 -- Martin Gargiulo and Mario Benassi (2000), 'Trapped in Your Own Net? Network Cohesion, Structural Holes, and the Adaptation of Social Capital', Organization Science, 11 (2), March/April, 183-96 -- Julia Porter Liebeskind and Amalya Lumerman Oliver (1998), 'From Handshake to Contract: Intellectual Property, Trust, and the Social Structure of Academic Research', in Christel Lane (ed) and Reinhard Bachmann (ed) (eds), Trust Within and Between Organizations: Conceptual Issues and Empirical Applications, Chapter 4, Oxford: Oxford University Press, 118-45 -- Mark Casson and Marina Della Giusta (2004), 'The Costly Business of Trust', Development Policy Review, 22 (3), 321-42 -- D. Harrison McKnight, Larry L. Cummings and Norman L. Chervany (1998), 'Initial Trust Formation in New Organizational Relationships', Academy of Management Review, 23 (3), July, 473-90",
                "This important two-volume set presents the most influential papers published in the field of trust research since the early 1960s. It reflects the key ideas on trust which have developed in various disciplines, including management studies, social psychology, organizational sociology and economics. The many topics covered include the foundations of trust research, the role of trust in economic exchange and trust as a fundamental social coordination mechanism. This reference collection will be invaluable to scholars wishing to keep abreast of progress in this most exciting and rapidly growing field"
